subSubSection.paragraph:
Head (
Fig. 20
): semicircular, as long as width (HW/HL = 1.16 , n = 20 ), widest at posterior part of eyes; setae on vertex rather dense, directed anteriomedially; punctation large, scattered rather densely; vertex longitudinally lack of punctation at middle, but medium in size. Eyes: medium in length, occupying approximately half length of head, slightly protruding laterally.

Mouth parts (
Figs 52–57
): mandible (
Fig. 54
) moderate in length, without conspicuous inner tooth. Labrum (
Fig 56
) moderately transverse, approximately 2.3 times as wide as long (excluding basal apodeme), anterior margin broadly and moderately emarginate medially; surface with pseudopores uniformly scattered rather densely. Epipharynx (
Fig. 57
) with a generalized athetine form, lateral margins with five thick spines on each side. Labial palpus (
Fig. 52
): setula a well-developed, situated near base of labial palpomere I; setulae b and c strongly developed. Maxilla (
Fig. 53
): lacinia with a distal comb consisting of consisting of approximately twenty thick spines; galea rather long and slender, as long as maxillary palpomere II; maxillary palpomere IV narrow but long, at least 1 / 2 as long as penultimate. Mentum (
Fig. 55
): anterior margin broadly emarginate, pseudopores scattered densely and uniformly except for laterobasal corners.

Antennae (
Fig. 38
): short, moderately shorter than head and pronotum combined; thick, setose, with antennomeres V to X strongly transverse in approximately same width each; antennomere XI symmetrical, obtusely rounded at apex; approximate relative length of antennomeres from basal to apex: 19 (including base): 8 : 11 : 4 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 14 .

Pronotum (
Fig. 2
): transversely oval (PW/PL = 1.40 , n = 20 ), rather strongly narrowing anterad, moderately longer than sutural length of elytra, widest basad of mid-length, basal margin weakly rounded; pubescence dense, directed laterally and posterolaterally; punctation small and shallow but dense and uniform.

Mesoventrite (
Fig. 29
): inter coxal process rather narrowly elongate, with rounded apex, completely reaching to inter coxal process of metaventrite.

Elytra (
Fig. 2
): together, transverse (EW/EL = 2.13 , n = 20 ), rather small, slightly smaller than pronotum, widest at middle; fine pubescence scattered densely, diverging posteriorly in each elytron; dorsal surface rough and impressed moderately; posterolateral corners of each elytron not sinuate.

Legs (
Fig. 2
): simple, short, moderately slender; fore and midtibia, densely covered with undeveloped spines, respectively.

Abdomen (
Fig. 2
): first three visible tergites deeply impressed transversely at base; dorsal and ventral surface moderately covered with thin and long setae.

Male : tergite VIII (
Fig. 58
): posterior margin smooth, not serrate at all, shallowly broadly emarginate medially; dorsal surface densely covered with setae, with approximately 11 macrosetae. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 60
): posterior margin nearly truncate, with a dense row of minute sensory setae (see
Yamamoto & Maruyama, 2012
: 10 ), without a complex-cluster of minute setae near posterior margin; ventral surface densely covered with setae, with approximately 13 macrosetae. Median lobe of aedeagus (
Figs 62–63
): [lateral view (
Fig. 62
)]: robust, gradually narrowing apically; apical lobe narrowing apically, moderately to strongly (usually strongly) hook-like shaped at apex; [parameral view (
Fig. 63
)]: bulbous, with basal part widely rounded; apical lobe abruptly narrowing near apex; a series of complex sclerites, reaching to almost basal margin of median lobe.

Female : tergite VIII (
Fig. 59
): posterior margin as in male; dorsal surface covered with setae densely, with approximately 13 macrosetae. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 61
): posterior margin very weakly rounded broadly or almost truncate; ventral surface covered with setae densely, with approximately 15 macrosetae; no complex-cluster of minute setae situated near posterior margin. Spermatheca (
Fig. 64
): C-shaped; apical invagination of spermatheca deep and conical in shape; spermathecal head and neck weakly deformed in elliptical shape; attachment of spermathecal duct inconspicuous; basal part of spermathecal stem widely curved, much longer than spermathecal head and neck combined; chitinized portion of spermathecal stem short, less than half length of spermathecal head and neck combined; each part of spermatheca uniformly and weakly sclerotized; inner wall of spermathecal head and neck rather densely striate, but that of basal part densely reticulate around middle to base.

Host records. At least four dipteran families are known as its host (
Maus et al ., 1998
): Anthomyiidae , Muscidae , Calliphoridae , Sarcophagidae and Syrphidae .
